<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="49" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; F. Tobar" authorityYear="2022" class="Aves" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Columnea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Columnea fluidifolia" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fluidifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Columnea fluidifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from most 
<taxonomicName class="Aves" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Columnea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Columnea" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Columnea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the presence of pendent elongate shoots and paired leaves that are both anisophyllous (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Columnea fluidifolia J. L. Clark &amp; F. Tobar A lateral view of mature flower B anisophyllous leaf pairs C isophyllous leaf pairs (base &amp; apex) and anisophyllous leaf pairs (middle) D immature berry E mature berry (A, B, D from J. L. Clark 16286 C, E from A. J. Perez &amp; F. Tobar sn). Photos A, B, D by J. L. Clark &amp; C, E by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.196.79673.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/683752" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">2A</figureCitation>
) and isophyllous (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Columnea fluidifolia J. L. Clark &amp; F. Tobar A lateral view of mature flower B anisophyllous leaf pairs C isophyllous leaf pairs (base &amp; apex) and anisophyllous leaf pairs (middle) D immature berry E mature berry (A, B, D from J. L. Clark 16286 C, E from A. J. Perez &amp; F. Tobar sn). Photos A, B, D by J. L. Clark &amp; C, E by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.196.79673.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/683752" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">2B</figureCitation>
). In addition, the shallowly bilabiate to tubular corolla and relatively large leaves (&gt; 4 cm long) are not typical for other 
<taxonomicName class="Aves" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Columnea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Columnea" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Columnea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with pendent elongate shoots. In contrast, most 
<taxonomicName class="Aves" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Columnea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Columnea" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Columnea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with pendent elongate shoots have corollas that are deeply bilabiate and small leaves (&lt;4 cm long). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J. L. Clark &amp; F. Tobar" authorityYear="2022" class="Aves" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Columnea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Columnea fluidifolia" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fluidifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Columnea fluidifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. ceticeps" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ceticeps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">C. ceticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The calyx lobes and corolla are orange in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. fluidifolia" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fluidifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">C. fluidifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Columnea fluidifolia J. L. Clark &amp; F. Tobar A lateral view of mature flower B anisophyllous leaf pairs C isophyllous leaf pairs (base &amp; apex) and anisophyllous leaf pairs (middle) D immature berry E mature berry (A, B, D from J. L. Clark 16286 C, E from A. J. Perez &amp; F. Tobar sn). Photos A, B, D by J. L. Clark &amp; C, E by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.196.79673.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/683752" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">2</figureCitation>
). In contrast, the calyx lobes are green, and the corolla is bright orange in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. ceticeps" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ceticeps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">C. ceticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Columnea ceticeps J. L. Clark &amp; J. F. Sm. A mature flower B pendent shoot C deeply bilabiate corolla D calyx lobes (A-D from J. L. Clark 12950 D photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.196.79673.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/683754" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">4</figureCitation>
). The corolla tube in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. fluidifolia" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fluidifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">C. fluidifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is nearly tubular without the presence of a bilabiate limb (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Columnea fluidifolia J. L. Clark &amp; F. Tobar A lateral view of mature flower B anisophyllous leaf pairs C isophyllous leaf pairs (base &amp; apex) and anisophyllous leaf pairs (middle) D immature berry E mature berry (A, B, D from J. L. Clark 16286 C, E from A. J. Perez &amp; F. Tobar sn). Photos A, B, D by J. L. Clark &amp; C, E by F. Tobar." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.196.79673.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/683752" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Columnea fluidifolia J. L. Clark &amp; F. Tobar A pendent shoot B lateral view of flower C bilobed dorsal nectary gland and ovary D mature calyx with style E stomatomorphic stigma F corolla opened featuring mature anthers G mature corolla. Illustration by M. J. Gavilanes." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.196.79673.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/683753" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">3</figureCitation>
). In contrast, the corolla tube in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="C." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. ceticeps" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ceticeps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">C. ceticeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is deeply bilabiate (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Columnea ceticeps J. L. Clark &amp; J. F. Sm. A mature flower B pendent shoot C deeply bilabiate corolla D calyx lobes (A-D from J. L. Clark 12950 D photos by J. L. Clark." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.196.79673.figure4" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/683754" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
